context: The French cleric Pierre Gassendi (<a0_0>1592-1665<a0_0/>) represented the materialist tradition in opposition to the attempts of <b5_0><b9_0>René Descartes<b9_0/><b5_0/> (<a1_0>1596-1650<a1_0/>) to provide the natural sciences with dualist foundations. There followed the materialist and atheist abbé Jean Meslier (<a2_0>1664-1729<a2_0/>), Julien Offray de La Mettrie, the German-French Paul-Henri Thiry Baron d'Holbach (1723-1789), the Encyclopedist Denis Diderot (<a3_0>1713-1784<a3_0/>), and <b6_0>other French Enlightenment thinkers<b6_0/>; as well as (in England) <b7_0><b8_0>John "Walking" Stewart<b8_0/><b7_0/> (1747-1822), whose insistence in seeing matter as endowed with a moral dimension had a major impact on the philosophical poetry of William Wordsworth (<a4_0>1770-1850<a4_0/>).
